{{italic title}} {{Coord|29.670853|N|95.617491|W|display=title}} {{Infobox artwork | image_file = quan-am-basic-setting-hh.jpg | painting_alignment = Front | image_size = 300px | title = Tượng Phật Quan Âm | alt = | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | artist = [[Mai Chi Kim]] | year = {{Start date|1998}} | type = Cast Concrete | height_imperial = 72 | width_imperial = | length_imperial = | imperial_unit = ft | metric_unit = m | city = [[Sugar Land, Texas|Sugar Land]], [[Texas]], [[United States]] | museum = | coordinates = | owner = }}
'''''Tượng Phật Quan Âm''''' ([[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]], [[English language|English]]: ''Buddha Statue of [[Avalokitesvara]]'') is a cast [[concrete]] [[statue]] in Chùa Việt Nam ('''English''': Vietnamese Buddhist Center) in [[Sugar Land, Texas|Sugar Land]], [[Texas]], just outside of [[Houston]]. The sculpture depicts the [[bodhisattva]] Avalokitesvara in female form standing on a lotus pedestal. She may also be commonly known by her Chinese name [[Guanyin]]. It was created by sculptor Mai Chi Kim,<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB1004061690676938720 "Quan Am, Texas-style"]</ref> who wanted to work on a bigger project after the temple had commissioned several smaller statues from her.
With the base included, the statue stands at 72 feet tall, making it one of the [[tallest statues in the United States]] and looks over a large pond beside an ornate red bridge. It is also suspected to be the largest Buddhist statue in the western hemisphere.<ref>[http://www.yourhoustonnews.com/fort_bend/news/roof-of-buddhist-temple-collapses-in-sugar-land-area/article_2a86d7cd-71e0-5d73-800e-ff57fa84439f.html "Roof of Buddhist temple collapses in Sugar Land area"]</ref>
Quan Am is one of the most highly revered bodhisattvas in [[Vietnam]] and is called by many epithets, including 'Mother of Buddhas' and 'Goddess of Compassion'.
